Fig. 8
shows maps of the degree of linear polarization of coronavirus model particles for different values of spike proteins. The X axis corresponds to the scattering angle values, and the Y axis - to the wavelengths. The degree of linear polarization is shown by different shades of gray: darker shades correspond to smaller polarization. An interesting polarization feature is observed in the spectral region of about 200 nm. If we consider it in more detail (see Fig. 9
), it becomes clear that it consists in a very sharp jump in the degree of linear polarization with increasing wavelength. This feature is clearly manifested in spherical particles and is called the Quasi–Rayleigh polarization leap (QRPL) [29]. QRPL can occur even at refractive indices close to 1, and depends on the scattering angle, on the size, on the refractive index, and on the shape of the scattering particle [30].
